Expected behavior of parseQuery with SPARQL 1.2
Current behavior
rdflib.plugins.sparql.parser.parseQuery throws ParseException on any SPARQL 1.2 syntax. The caller gets nothing — there is no partial parse, no structured error, no fallback.

Expected behavior
parseQuery (or a Starlight-provided equivalent) accepts the full SPARQL 1.2 grammar and returns a typed parse tree. The six new constructs are:

1. Triple terms in subject/object position

<<( ?s ?p ?o )>> ex:certainty ?c .
Currently: parse error.

Expected: a TripleTerm node in the subject slot of the triple, containing its own subject, predicate, object child nodes — the same types that can appear in any triple (variables, IRIs, literals, or nested triple terms).

Triple terms must be preserved in the parse tree, not rewritten to reification. The rewriting is Starlight's job at execution time; the parse tree should reflect what the user wrote.

2. TRIPLE(s, p, o) — triple-term constructor

BIND(TRIPLE(?s, ?p, ?o) AS ?t)
Currently: parse error (TRIPLE is not a known function name).

Expected: a Builtin_TRIPLE (or Function_TRIPLE) node with three argument slots — same shape as other three-argument builtins like IF.

3. SUBJECT(?t), PREDICATE(?t), OBJECT(?t) — accessor functions

BIND(SUBJECT(?t) AS ?s)
FILTER(OBJECT(?t) = ex:bob)
Currently: parse error.

Expected: Builtin_SUBJECT, Builtin_PREDICATE, Builtin_OBJECT nodes with one argument each — same shape as any single-argument builtin like STR.

4. isTripleTerm(?x) — type predicate

FILTER(isTripleTerm(?t))
Currently: parse error (the function name is unknown to the grammar).

Expected: a Builtin_isTripleTerm node with one argument — same shape as isIRI, isBlank, etc.

5. Annotation syntax {| prop value |}

?s ex:knows ?o {| ex:certainty ?c |}
Currently: parse error.

Expected: an Annotation node attached to the enclosing triple, containing a property-value list. This is the most complex addition — the grammar production wraps a triple and its annotation block together.

6. Annotation subject << s p o >> pred obj

<< ex:alice ex:knows ex:bob >> ex:certainty ?c .
Currently: parse error.

Expected: a ReifiedTriple node in subject position, distinct from TripleTerm — it denotes the reifier of the named triple rather than the triple term itself.

Why preserved structure matters
If the parser rewrites (like the current rewrite_sparql12_to_11 text rewriter does), the caller gets reification triples — the original intent is lost. A structural editor needs TripleTerm { subject: ?s, predicate: ?p, object: ?o } to be able to display and edit it. Reification triples give the editor no way to know a triple term was there. The rewriting to SPARQL 1.1 belongs at the execution layer, not the parse layer.